description.p:
Typically, polyalkene-substituted amines are prepared by reacting
halogenated-, preferably chlorinated-, olefins and olefin polymers (polyalkenes)
with amines (mono- or polyamines). The amines may be any of the amines
described above. Examples of these compounds include poly(propylene)amine;
N,N-dimethyl-N-poly (ethylene/propylene)amine, (50:50 mole ratio of monomers);
polybutene amine; N,N-di(hydroxyethyl)-N-polybutene amine; N-(2-hydroxypropyl)-N-polybutene
amine; N-polybutene-aniline; N-polybutenemorpholine;
N-poly(butene) ethylenediamine; N-poly(propylene)trimethylenediamine;
N-poly(butene)diethylene-triamine; N',N'-poly(butene)tetraethylenepentamine;
N,N-dimethyl-N'-poly(propylene)-1,3-propylenediamine and the
like.
